// content/y10/geography/islands/x01.js — Year 10 Geography Topic 1: The Challenge of Natural Hazards — expansion pack (3 flashcards + 10 questions per island). All items original.

// ── FLASHCARDS ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
FLASHCARDS.push(
  // g10i-01-1 — Tectonic Hazards
  {id:"g10fc-01-1-6", islandId:"g10i-01-1", front:"Describe the internal structure of the Earth and how it drives plate movement.",
   back:"The Earth has four main layers:\n\n• Inner core — solid iron and nickel, extremely hot (~5,500 °C).\n• Outer core — liquid iron and nickel; its movement generates the magnetic field.\n• Mantle — semi-molten rock; the upper mantle (asthenosphere) flows slowly.\n• Crust — thin, rigid outer layer (oceanic crust is dense and thin; continental crust is thick and less dense).\n\nHeat from the core, partly from radioactive decay, sets up convection currents in the mantle. These currents drag the rigid lithospheric plates above them. Slab pull (a dense subducting plate sinking and pulling the rest with it) and ridge push are now seen as the main driving forces.", difficulty:2, category:"concept"},
  {id:"g10fc-01-1-7", islandId:"g10i-01-1", front:"Explain how a submarine earthquake can generate a tsunami.",
   back:"A tsunami is usually triggered at a destructive (subduction) boundary beneath the sea:\n\n1. The subducting plate sticks against the overriding plate and strain builds up.\n2. When the fault suddenly slips, the seabed is thrust upwards, displacing a huge volume of water.\n3. The displaced water spreads out as a series of long, fast, low waves in the open ocean.\n4. As the waves reach shallow coastal water they slow down, bunch together and grow rapidly in height.\n\nThe 2011 Tohoku earthquake (M9.0) displaced the seabed off Japan and generated waves up to 40 m high in places, causing most of the ~18,500 deaths and triggering the Fukushima nuclear disaster.", difficulty:3, category:"process"},
  {id:"g10fc-01-1-8", islandId:"g10i-01-1", front:"Compare immediate and long-term responses to a tectonic hazard.",
   back:"Immediate responses (hours to days):\n• Search and rescue to free trapped people\n• Treating the injured; setting up emergency shelters\n• Providing clean water, food and medicine\n• Restoring power and communications\n• International aid teams and supplies\n\nLong-term responses (weeks to years):\n• Rebuilding homes, hospitals and infrastructure, often to higher standards\n• Repairing or upgrading earthquake-resistant defences\n• Restoring the economy and people's livelihoods\n• Reviewing building codes and emergency plans\n• Counselling for psychological trauma\n\nHICs can usually fund both stages themselves; LICs often rely on international aid and recovery takes far longer.", difficulty:2, category:"concept"},

  // g10i-01-2 — Weather Hazards
  {id:"g10fc-01-2-6", islandId:"g10i-01-2", front:"Explain how the Coriolis effect influences global surface winds.",
   back:"The Coriolis effect is the apparent deflection of moving air caused by the Earth's rotation:\n\n• In the Northern Hemisphere winds are deflected to the right; in the Southern Hemisphere to the left.\n• This turns winds blowing from high to low pressure into curved paths rather than straight lines.\n\nIt explains the direction of the major surface winds:\n• Trade winds blow from the subtropical high (~30°) towards the Equator, deflected to become north-easterlies (N hemisphere) and south-easterlies (S hemisphere).\n• Westerlies blow from ~30° towards 60°, deflected to become south-westerlies in the Northern Hemisphere — these bring mild, wet weather to the UK.\n\nThe effect is strongest at the poles and zero at the Equator.", difficulty:2, category:"process"},
  {id:"g10fc-01-2-7", islandId:"g10i-01-2", front:"How is a Saffir-Simpson style scale used to classify tropical storms?",
   back:"Tropical storms are graded by sustained wind speed on a five-category scale:\n\n• Category 1 (119–153 km/h) — some damage to roofs and trees.\n• Category 2 (154–177 km/h) — extensive damage; power loss likely.\n• Category 3 (178–208 km/h) — major damage; classed as a 'major' storm.\n• Category 4 (209–251 km/h) — severe damage; areas uninhabitable for weeks.\n• Category 5 (over 252 km/h) — catastrophic; most buildings destroyed.\n\nThe scale is based on wind speed alone and does not measure the rainfall or storm surge, which often cause the most deaths. Typhoon Haiyan (2013), with winds around 315 km/h, was a Category 5 storm.", difficulty:2, category:"concept"},
  {id:"g10fc-01-2-8", islandId:"g10i-01-2", front:"Explain how warning, planning and protection reduce the impacts of weather hazards.",
   back:"Warning and prediction:\n• Satellites and weather aircraft track tropical storms days ahead, allowing evacuation.\n• The Met Office issues colour-coded warnings for UK storms and floods.\n\nPlanning:\n• Evacuation routes, emergency shelters and stockpiled supplies are prepared in advance.\n• Education campaigns teach people how to respond.\n• Land-use planning keeps development off floodplains.\n\nProtection:\n• Storm-resistant buildings and reinforced shelters.\n• Sea walls, flood barriers and levees reduce surge and flood damage.\n• Restoring mangroves and wetlands absorbs storm energy and floodwater.\n\nA combination is most effective: warning saves lives, protection reduces property damage, and planning ties the response together.", difficulty:3, category:"evaluation"},

  // g10i-01-3 — Climate Change
  {id:"g10fc-01-3-6", islandId:"g10i-01-3", front:"Describe the likely effects of climate change on people and the environment.",
   back:"Effects on the environment:\n• Melting ice sheets and glaciers; shrinking Arctic sea ice.\n• Rising sea levels from thermal expansion and ice melt.\n• More frequent and intense droughts, floods and heatwaves.\n• Warming and acidifying oceans damaging coral reefs.\n• Shifting ecosystems and species ranges; some extinctions.\n\nEffects on people:\n• Low-lying coasts and islands flooded; coastal communities displaced.\n• Changing rainfall harms farming, threatening food and water security.\n• Spread of tropical diseases such as malaria to new areas.\n• Damage to infrastructure from extreme weather.\n• Climate migration and pressure on resources.\n\nLICs are often hit hardest despite contributing least to emissions.", difficulty:2, category:"application"},
  {id:"g10fc-01-3-7", islandId:"g10i-01-3", front:"How does methane compare with carbon dioxide as a greenhouse gas?",
   back:"Both are greenhouse gases that trap outgoing long-wave radiation, but they differ:\n\n• Carbon dioxide (CO2) — released mainly by burning fossil fuels, deforestation and cement production. It is the largest single contributor to the enhanced greenhouse effect because it is emitted in vast quantities and lingers in the atmosphere for centuries.\n• Methane (CH4) — released by livestock (cattle), rice paddies, landfill and thawing permafrost. Per molecule it is a far more powerful greenhouse gas than CO2 (over 25 times stronger over 100 years), but it is emitted in smaller amounts and breaks down within about a decade.\n\nCutting methane gives quicker short-term cooling, while cutting CO2 matters most for the long term.", difficulty:3, category:"concept"},
  {id:"g10fc-01-3-8", islandId:"g10i-01-3", front:"How can individuals and local actions help tackle climate change?",
   back:"While international agreements set the framework, individual and local action also reduces emissions:\n\n• Transport — walking, cycling, using public transport and electric vehicles instead of petrol or diesel cars.\n• Energy — insulating homes, using LED lighting and switching to renewable electricity tariffs.\n• Diet — eating less meat and dairy, and reducing food waste, cuts methane and land use.\n• Consumption — reusing and recycling reduces the energy used in manufacturing.\n• Local schemes — community renewable projects, tree-planting and congestion charging (e.g. low-emission zones in cities).\n\nThese actions are small individually but significant collectively, and they support the larger mitigation efforts of governments and businesses.", difficulty:2, category:"application"},

  // g10i-01-4 — Tropical Storms
  {id:"g10fc-01-4-6", islandId:"g10i-01-4", front:"Why do tropical storms have different names in different parts of the world?",
   back:"Tropical storms are the same phenomenon — an intense rotating low-pressure system — but the name depends on where they form:\n\n• Hurricane — in the North Atlantic, Caribbean and north-east Pacific (e.g. affecting the USA and Caribbean).\n• Typhoon — in the north-west Pacific (e.g. affecting Japan, the Philippines and China).\n• Cyclone — in the Indian Ocean and around northern Australia (e.g. affecting Bangladesh and India).\n\nThe naming is purely regional convention. All three require the same conditions: warm ocean water over 26.5 °C, a sufficient depth of warm water, low wind shear and a latitude of 5°–30° for the Coriolis effect to create spin.", difficulty:1, category:"concept"},
  {id:"g10fc-01-4-7", islandId:"g10i-01-4", front:"Why is the storm surge often the most dangerous part of a tropical storm?",
   back:"A storm surge is a rise in sea level caused by a tropical storm:\n\n• The intense low pressure at the centre lets the sea surface bulge upwards.\n• Powerful onshore winds pile water against the coast.\n• The surge is highest where the storm makes landfall and is worse on low-lying, funnel-shaped coastlines.\n\nIt is so dangerous because:\n• Sea water floods large areas of low-lying land rapidly, drowning people and livestock.\n• It destroys buildings, contaminates farmland with salt and pollutes fresh water.\n• It causes a high proportion of tropical-storm deaths — for example the 5 m surge at Tacloban during Typhoon Haiyan (2013).\n\nWind-speed scales alone do not capture this surge risk.", difficulty:3, category:"process"},
  {id:"g10fc-01-4-8", islandId:"g10i-01-4", front:"Evaluate how monitoring, prediction and protection reduce the impact of tropical storms.",
   back:"Monitoring and prediction:\n+ Satellites and aircraft track storms days in advance, allowing timely evacuation.\n+ Computer models forecast the likely track and strength.\n- Exact landfall and intensity remain uncertain, and evacuation is costly.\n\nProtection:\n+ Storm-resistant buildings on stilts and reinforced shelters save lives.\n+ Sea walls and restored mangroves reduce storm-surge damage.\n- Expensive — hard for LICs to fund at scale.\n\nPlanning:\n+ Evacuation routes, drills and stockpiled supplies reduce deaths.\n+ Relatively low cost.\n- Relies on good communication and public cooperation.\n\nConclusion: prediction and evacuation save the most lives, while protection limits property damage; a combination tailored to a country's wealth works best.", difficulty:3, category:"evaluation"},

  // g10i-01-5 — Reducing Tectonic Hazard Risk
  {id:"g10fc-01-5-6", islandId:"g10i-01-5", front:"What is the difference between a hazard, a disaster and risk?",
   back:"These terms are often confused but mean different things:\n\n• Hazard — a natural event that threatens people or property (e.g. an earthquake or volcanic eruption). On its own, in an empty area, it is just a natural event.\n• Disaster — occurs when a hazard seriously affects a vulnerable population, causing significant loss of life, damage or disruption that the community cannot cope with alone.\n• Risk — the probability that a hazard will cause harm. Risk rises where more people live in exposed locations, where they are poor or poorly prepared, and where the hazard is frequent or intense.\n\nReducing vulnerability through protection and planning lowers the risk, so a hazard is less likely to become a disaster.", difficulty:2, category:"concept"},
  {id:"g10fc-01-5-7", islandId:"g10i-01-5", front:"How does the Park model (disaster response curve) describe recovery after a hazard?",
   back:"The Park model (hazard-response curve) plots quality of life or economic activity over time before, during and after a disaster:\n\n• Stage 1 — Pre-disaster: normal life; preparedness reduces the fall.\n• Stage 2 — Relief (hours to days): quality of life drops sharply; search, rescue and emergency aid.\n• Stage 3 — Rehabilitation (days to weeks): temporary services restored; shelter, water and food provided.\n• Stage 4 — Reconstruction (weeks to years): rebuilding to restore or improve on the original quality of life.\n\nThe curve shows that better preparation makes the drop shallower, and effective response and reconstruction make recovery faster — and a community may end up better off than before if it 'builds back better'.", difficulty:3, category:"concept"},
  {id:"g10fc-01-5-8", islandId:"g10i-01-5", front:"How can education and emergency drills reduce the death toll from earthquakes?",
   back:"Education and drills are a low-cost but highly effective planning strategy:\n\n• People learn protective actions such as 'drop, cover and hold on', and to move away from windows and tall furniture.\n• Schools and workplaces practise evacuation so movement is quick and orderly, reducing panic and crush injuries.\n• Communities learn how to shut off gas and electricity to prevent fires after a quake.\n• People know where emergency shelters and assembly points are, speeding up the response.\n• Households are encouraged to keep emergency kits (water, torch, first aid).\n\nJapan's annual Disaster Prevention Day on 1 September rehearses millions of people, which is one reason its earthquake death tolls are far lower than the magnitude alone would suggest.", difficulty:2, category:"application"},

  // g10i-01-6 — UK Extreme Weather
  {id:"g10fc-01-6-6", islandId:"g10i-01-6", front:"How does the UK's position give it such varied weather?",
   back:"The UK has changeable weather because it lies where several air masses meet:\n\n• Tropical maritime — warm, moist air from the south-west Atlantic; brings mild, wet, cloudy weather (the most common).\n• Polar maritime — cool, moist air from the north-west; brings cold, showery weather.\n• Polar continental — cold, dry air from the east in winter; brings freezing conditions and snow (the 'Beast from the East').\n• Tropical continental — warm, dry air from the south in summer; brings heatwaves.\n• Arctic maritime — very cold air from the north; brings snow and frost.\n\nThe UK also sits in the path of the mid-latitude depressions carried on the prevailing south-westerly winds, which bring frequent fronts, rain and wind.", difficulty:2, category:"concept"},
  {id:"g10fc-01-6-7", islandId:"g10i-01-6", front:"How does a depression bring a sequence of weather to the UK?",
   back:"A depression is an area of low pressure where warm and cold air masses meet along fronts:\n\n1. Warm front arrives first — warm air rises gently over cold air, bringing thickening cloud and steady, prolonged rain.\n2. Warm sector follows — milder, with drizzle or brighter skies and lower pressure.\n3. Cold front passes — cold air undercuts the warm air, forcing it to rise steeply; this brings heavy showers, gusty winds and a temperature drop.\n4. Clearance — pressure rises and brighter, cooler conditions return behind the front.\n\nDeep, fast-moving depressions in winter are named by the Met Office and can bring damaging gales and flooding, such as Storm Desmond in 2015.", difficulty:3, category:"process"},
  {id:"g10fc-01-6-8", islandId:"g10i-01-6", front:"Evaluate hard and soft engineering approaches to managing UK flooding.",
   back:"Hard engineering (built structures):\n+ Flood walls, embankments and barriers (e.g. the Thames Barrier) give strong, reliable protection.\n+ Dredging increases river capacity.\n- Expensive to build and maintain; can shift the flood problem downstream; can look unnatural.\n\nSoft engineering (working with natural processes):\n+ Floodplain restoration, tree planting and 'leaky dams' slow run-off and store water upstream.\n+ Usually cheaper and benefits wildlife and water quality.\n- Slower to take effect; needs large areas of land; may not cope with extreme events alone.\n\nConclusion: a catchment-wide approach combining both works best — soft measures reduce the volume and speed of run-off while hard defences protect high-value urban areas such as Carlisle.", difficulty:3, category:"evaluation"}
);

// ── STATIC QUESTION BANKS ───────────────────────────────────────────────────
QUESTIONS["g10i-01-1"] = (QUESTIONS["g10i-01-1"] || []).concat([
  {q:"Which layer of the Earth is liquid and responsible for generating its magnetic field?",
   opts:["The inner core","The outer core","The mantle","The crust"], c:1,
   e:"The outer core is liquid iron and nickel, and its movement generates the Earth's magnetic field. The inner core is also iron and nickel but is solid because of the immense pressure, so it cannot flow to create the field. The mantle is semi-molten rock and the crust is the thin, rigid outer layer."},
  {q:"What is now thought to be a major driving force of plate movement at destructive boundaries?",
   opts:["Slab pull, as a dense subducting plate sinks and drags the rest of the plate with it","The pull of the Moon's gravity on the plates","The rotation of the Earth flinging plates outwards","Pressure from the solid inner core pushing upwards"], c:0,
   e:"Slab pull occurs when a dense oceanic plate subducts and sinks into the mantle, dragging the rest of the plate behind it. Along with ridge push, this is now regarded as a major driver of plate motion, working alongside mantle convection currents. The Moon's gravity drives tides, not plate tectonics, and the Earth's rotation does not move plates."},
  {q:"At a constructive plate boundary, why are eruptions usually gentle rather than explosive?",
   opts:["The magma is thick and sticky, trapping gases","The magma is runny basaltic lava, so gases escape easily and it flows rather than explodes","No magma reaches the surface at constructive boundaries","The plates are moving together, squeezing the magma"], c:1,
   e:"At constructive boundaries plates diverge and runny basaltic magma rises to fill the gap. Because this lava is fluid, gases escape easily and it flows out gently, as in Iceland. Explosive eruptions occur at destructive boundaries, where thick, sticky andesitic or rhyolitic magma traps gas until it erupts violently. The distinction is the type and viscosity of the magma."},
  {q:"How is a tsunami generated by a submarine earthquake?",
   opts:["Heavy rainfall raises sea levels rapidly","Strong winds push waves towards the coast","Sudden movement of the seabed displaces a large volume of water","The sea is heated by underwater lava"], c:2,
   e:"At a subduction zone the seabed is suddenly thrust upwards when the locked fault slips, displacing a huge volume of water that spreads out as fast, low waves. These slow and grow in height as they reach shallow coastal water. Wind-driven waves are a weather process, and rainfall or heating do not produce tsunami; a tsunami is a direct result of seabed displacement."},
  {q:"Which of the following is the best example of a primary effect of a volcanic eruption?",
   opts:["Famine caused by destroyed farmland months later","Buildings buried and people killed by fast-moving pyroclastic flows during the eruption","Tourism declining in the following year","Disease spreading in crowded evacuation camps"], c:1,
   e:"Primary effects are the immediate, direct results of the eruption itself. People killed and buildings buried by pyroclastic flows happen during the event, so they are primary. Famine from lost farmland, falling tourism and disease in camps are all knock-on consequences that develop afterwards, making them secondary effects."},
  {q:"Roughly what proportion of the world's earthquakes occur around the Pacific 'Ring of Fire'?",
   opts:["About 10%","About 25%","About 50%","About 90%"], c:3,
   e:"Around 90% of the world's earthquakes, and about 75% of its active volcanoes, occur around the Pacific Ring of Fire. This is because the Pacific Plate meets several other plates at destructive boundaries here. The figure is high precisely because tectonic activity is concentrated at plate margins rather than spread evenly across the globe."},
  {q:"A country with a high GDP per person suffers a magnitude 7 earthquake with very few deaths. Which factor best explains this?",
   opts:["High-magnitude earthquakes always cause few deaths","Wealth allowed investment in earthquake-resistant buildings, drills and rapid emergency services","The earthquake must have struck an uninhabited region","Wealthy countries never lie near plate boundaries"], c:1,
   e:"Wealth allows a country to enforce strict building codes, invest in earthquake-resistant design, run regular drills and fund well-equipped emergency services, all of which reduce deaths. Magnitude alone does not determine the death toll — a lower-magnitude quake in a poor, unprepared country can kill far more. Many wealthy countries, such as Japan, lie directly on plate boundaries."},
  {q:"Why might a magnitude 6 earthquake in a low-income country cause more deaths than a magnitude 8 earthquake in a high-income country?",
   opts:["A magnitude 6 releases more energy than a magnitude 8","Poorly built housing, limited emergency services and high vulnerability outweigh the lower magnitude","Earthquakes are stronger near the Equator","Low-income countries experience deeper earthquakes"], c:1,
   e:"Although a magnitude 8 releases far more energy than a magnitude 6, the impact depends on vulnerability. In a low-income country, unreinforced buildings collapse easily, emergency services are limited and poverty slows recovery, so even a moderate quake can be deadly. In a high-income country, earthquake-resistant buildings and rapid response keep deaths low even in a much stronger event."},
  {q:"Most of the ~18,500 deaths in the 2011 Tohoku (Japan) disaster were caused by which factor?",
   opts:["Collapsing buildings during the shaking","Volcanic ash from a nearby eruption","Landslides in the mountains","The tsunami that followed the earthquake"], c:3,
   e:"Japan's strict building codes meant most structures survived the M9.0 shaking itself. The great majority of deaths were caused by the tsunami generated when the seabed was displaced offshore, which swept inland and also triggered the Fukushima nuclear disaster. This shows that for coastal subduction zones, the secondary tsunami hazard can be far deadlier than the shaking."},
  {q:"Evaluate why relying only on earthquake-resistant building design may not fully protect an LIC community.",
   opts:["Earthquake-resistant design is cheap and easy for any country to apply everywhere","Such design is expensive, so an LIC may not afford it widely, and planning and education are also needed to reduce risk","Building design prevents earthquakes from occurring","Resistant buildings remove the need for any emergency services"], c:1,
   e:"Earthquake-resistant construction is highly effective but costly, so an LIC may only be able to apply it to a few key buildings, leaving much housing vulnerable. It also does not address tsunami risk, fires or the need for rescue. A combined approach — affordable protection plus low-cost planning, drills and education — gives broader protection. Building design reduces damage but cannot prevent the earthquake itself or replace emergency planning."}
]);

QUESTIONS["g10i-01-2"] = (QUESTIONS["g10i-01-2"] || []).concat([
  {q:"At approximately 30° north and south, air sinks. What weather does this create at the surface?",
   opts:["High pressure with dry, clear conditions, forming the world's major hot deserts","Low pressure with heavy convectional rainfall","Frontal rainfall where two air masses meet","Constant strong winds and storms"], c:0,
   e:"At about 30° the descending limb of the Hadley Cell creates high pressure. Sinking air warms and holds its moisture, so skies are clear and dry, forming hot deserts such as the Sahara. Heavy convectional rainfall occurs where air rises at the Equator, and frontal rainfall occurs around 60° where the Ferrel and Polar cells meet, not at 30°."},
  {q:"In which direction does the Coriolis effect deflect surface winds in the Northern Hemisphere?",
   opts:["To the left","To the right","Straight towards the Equator with no deflection","Vertically upwards"], c:1,
   e:"In the Northern Hemisphere the Coriolis effect deflects moving air to the right; in the Southern Hemisphere it deflects to the left. This turns winds blowing out of high-pressure zones into curved paths, producing the trade winds and the south-westerly westerlies that bring mild, wet weather to the UK. The effect is caused by the Earth's rotation and is zero at the Equator."},
  {q:"Why do the prevailing south-westerly winds bring mild, wet weather to the UK?",
   opts:["They come from the cold polar regions","They blow across the warm Atlantic Ocean, picking up heat and moisture","They form over the Sahara Desert","They are dry winds descending from high altitude"], c:1,
   e:"The UK's prevailing winds are south-westerlies that travel across the relatively warm Atlantic Ocean. They pick up heat and moisture, so they arrive mild and damp, bringing cloud and rain, especially in winter. These are part of the Ferrel Cell westerlies, deflected to the right by the Coriolis effect. They do not originate over the poles or deserts."},
  {q:"A tropical storm is classified as Category 5 on a Saffir-Simpson style scale. What does this tell us?",
   opts:["It has the slowest wind speeds and causes little damage","It has the highest sustained wind speeds (over 252 km/h) and is likely to cause catastrophic damage","It is no longer over warm water","It has weakened to a tropical depression"], c:1,
   e:"Category 5 is the top of the five-point scale, with sustained winds over 252 km/h and the potential for catastrophic, widespread destruction. Category 1 is the weakest. However, the scale measures wind speed only — it does not capture the rainfall or storm surge, which often cause the most deaths, so a high category does not tell the whole story of a storm's danger."},
  {q:"Why does releasing latent heat make a developing tropical storm stronger?",
   opts:["It cools the air, making it sink and spread out","It freezes the cloud droplets, stopping the storm","As water vapour condenses it releases heat, warming the air so it rises faster and draws in more warm, moist air","It increases the salinity of the ocean below"], c:2,
   e:"As warm, moist air rises and cools, water vapour condenses into cloud and releases latent heat. This warms the surrounding air, making it more buoyant so it rises even faster. This deepens the low pressure and draws in more warm, moist air from the surface, intensifying the storm in a self-reinforcing cycle. The process adds energy, rather than cooling or stopping the storm."},
  {q:"Why does a tropical storm rapidly weaken once it moves over land?",
   opts:["The land heats the storm and makes it spin faster","It is cut off from the warm ocean water that supplies its heat and moisture","The Coriolis effect disappears over land","Rainfall over land adds energy to the storm"], c:1,
   e:"A tropical storm is powered by heat and moisture evaporating from warm ocean water. Over land this energy supply is removed, and friction with the land surface slows the winds, so the storm quickly weakens and dies out. The Coriolis effect still acts over land; it is the loss of the ocean heat source, not the loss of spin, that causes the storm to decay."},
  {q:"During Typhoon Haiyan (2013), what was the main cause of devastation in the coastal city of Tacloban?",
   opts:["A volcanic eruption","A 5-metre storm surge that flooded the low-lying city","A prolonged drought","An earthquake beneath the city"], c:1,
   e:"Much of the devastation in Tacloban came from a storm surge around 5 metres high, which flooded the low-lying coastal city and contributed to the high death toll of over 6,300. Although the winds reached about 315 km/h, it was the surge that caused the most widespread loss of life. The event was a weather hazard, not a tectonic one, so a volcano or earthquake was not involved."},
  {q:"Which statement best explains how climate change is expected to affect tropical storms?",
   opts:["There will definitely be far more storms each year","A greater proportion of storms may become more intense, with heavier rainfall and bigger storm surges","Storms will start forming directly on the Equator","Warmer oceans will cause storms to disappear"], c:1,
   e:"Warmer sea surface temperatures provide more energy, so a greater proportion of storms are expected to reach high intensity. Warmer air holds about 7% more moisture per 1 °C, increasing rainfall, and higher sea levels worsen storm surges. The total number of storms may not rise much, and they still cannot form on the Equator because the Coriolis effect there is too weak."},
  {q:"Storm Desmond (2015) brought 341.4 mm of rain in 24 hours to Honister Pass. Why was this so significant?",
   opts:["It was a record-breaking daily rainfall total for the UK at the time, overwhelming flood defences in Cumbria","It was an average amount of rain for a UK winter day","It fell as snow, causing no flooding","It was rainfall measured over a whole month"], c:0,
   e:"The 341.4 mm in 24 hours was a record daily rainfall total for the UK at the time, delivered by an atmospheric river. Such an extreme amount of rain in one day overwhelmed flood defences in Carlisle, flooded over 5,200 homes and caused damage costing over £500 million. This represents a single day, not a month, and it fell as rain rather than snow."},
  {q:"Evaluate why a coastal LIC might struggle to reduce the impacts of tropical storms despite good forecasting.",
   opts:["Forecasting removes all need for any other measures","Forecasting causes storms to strengthen","LICs are never affected by tropical storms","Even with warnings, poverty may limit storm-resistant buildings, evacuation transport and sea defences, so impacts remain high"], c:3,
   e:"Good forecasting helps people prepare and evacuate, but it cannot by itself protect property or those unable to leave. A coastal LIC may lack the money for storm-resistant housing, transport to evacuate everyone and sea defences against the surge, so impacts stay high. Effective management needs forecasting combined with affordable protection and planning. Forecasting does not strengthen storms, and LICs such as the Philippines are frequently hit."}
]);

QUESTIONS["g10i-01-3"] = (QUESTIONS["g10i-01-3"] || []).concat([
  {q:"Which of these is a likely environmental effect of climate change?",
   opts:["Falling global sea levels","Coral reefs being damaged by warmer, more acidic oceans","An increase in Arctic sea ice","Cooling of the deep oceans"], c:1,
   e:"Warmer oceans, combined with acidification as they absorb CO2, cause coral bleaching and damage reef ecosystems. Climate change is also raising sea levels through thermal expansion and ice melt, and reducing Arctic sea ice, not increasing it. The deep oceans are warming overall, so a rise in ice or a fall in sea level would be inconsistent with the observed evidence."},
  {q:"Per molecule, how does methane compare with carbon dioxide as a greenhouse gas?",
   opts:["Methane is much weaker than carbon dioxide","Methane is a far more powerful greenhouse gas per molecule but is emitted in smaller amounts and breaks down faster","They are identical in every way","Methane does not trap any heat at all"], c:1,
   e:"Per molecule, methane traps far more heat than carbon dioxide (over 25 times more over a century), but it is released in much smaller quantities and breaks down within about a decade. Carbon dioxide is emitted in vast amounts and persists for centuries, so it is the largest overall contributor. Both trap long-wave radiation, so they are not identical and methane is certainly not inert."},
  {q:"Which of the following is a mitigation strategy rather than an adaptation strategy?",
   opts:["Building higher sea walls to cope with rising seas","Generating electricity from wind and solar instead of coal","Breeding drought-resistant crops","Moving communities away from flooding coasts"], c:1,
   e:"Mitigation reduces greenhouse gas emissions to slow climate change. Switching from coal to wind and solar cuts CO2 emissions, so it is mitigation. Higher sea walls, drought-resistant crops and managed retreat all adjust to changes already happening, so they are adaptation. The key test is whether the strategy tackles the cause (mitigation) or copes with the effects (adaptation)."},
  {q:"Why can Milankovitch cycles not explain the rapid warming of the last 150 years?",
   opts:["They cause cooling, never warming","They operate over tens of thousands of years, far too slowly to account for rapid recent warming","They only affect the Southern Hemisphere","They are caused by burning fossil fuels"], c:1,
   e:"Milankovitch cycles are slow variations in the Earth's orbit, tilt and wobble that operate over tens of thousands of years and drive the ice-age cycles. They are far too gradual to explain the sharp warming seen over the past 150 years, which matches the rise in human greenhouse-gas emissions instead. They are a natural cause, not a result of burning fossil fuels, and they can drive both warming and cooling globally."},
  {q:"How do ice cores provide evidence of past climate?",
   opts:["They contain fossils of ancient sea creatures","They show the thickness of modern glaciers only","Trapped air bubbles preserve samples of past atmospheres, recording CO2 levels and temperature","They record human population over time"], c:2,
   e:"As snow compacts into ice it traps tiny air bubbles. Drilling deep into Antarctic ice sheets retrieves these bubbles, which preserve samples of the atmosphere stretching back over 800,000 years, allowing scientists to reconstruct past CO2 levels and temperatures. They show current CO2 (~420 ppm) is the highest in that record. Ice cores capture trapped air, not fossils or population data."},
  {q:"Why are many low-income countries expected to be hit hardest by climate change?",
   opts:["They produce the most greenhouse gas emissions","They often have less money to adapt and rely heavily on climate-sensitive farming, despite contributing least to emissions","They are all located at the poles","Climate change only affects poorer countries"], c:1,
   e:"Many low-income countries depend on rain-fed farming and have limited funds for flood defences, irrigation or relief, so droughts, floods and rising seas hit them hard. Yet they have contributed least to global emissions, which is why this is seen as an issue of climate justice. Climate change affects all countries, and the highest emitters historically have been wealthier, industrialised nations, not the poorest."},
  {q:"The 2015 Paris Agreement set a target to limit global warming to which level?",
   opts:["Well below 2 °C, aiming for 1.5 °C above pre-industrial levels","Exactly 5 °C above pre-industrial levels","No specific temperature target at all","A reduction to pre-industrial temperatures within ten years"], c:0,
   e:"Under the Paris Agreement, 196 countries agreed to limit warming to well below 2 °C, while pursuing efforts to keep it to 1.5 °C, above pre-industrial levels. The target is ambitious but the pledges (NDCs) are voluntary and currently insufficient to guarantee it. A 5 °C rise would be catastrophic rather than a goal, and reversing to pre-industrial temperatures within a decade is not realistic."},
  {q:"Which individual action would most directly reduce a person's greenhouse gas emissions?",
   opts:["Leaving lights and devices on continuously","Cycling or using public transport instead of driving a petrol car","Increasing the amount of meat in their diet","Buying more single-use plastic products"], c:1,
   e:"Cycling or using public transport instead of a petrol car directly cuts the CO2 released from burning fuel, reducing a person's emissions. Leaving devices on wastes energy and raises emissions, eating more meat increases methane from livestock, and buying more single-use plastic adds to manufacturing emissions and waste. The effective choice is the one that lowers fossil-fuel use."},
  {q:"A graph shows global CO2 rising steadily since 1850 alongside rising average temperatures. What does this best support?",
   opts:["That temperature controls how much CO2 humans burn","That rising CO2 from human activity is closely linked to the observed warming","That CO2 and temperature are unrelated","That the climate is cooling overall"], c:1,
   e:"A close correlation between rising CO2 since industrialisation and rising global temperatures supports the scientific consensus that human-caused CO2 emissions are driving the warming. Although correlation alone does not prove cause, it fits the physics of the enhanced greenhouse effect. The data show warming, not cooling, and it is human emissions raising CO2, not temperature controlling how much fuel is burned."},
  {q:"Evaluate why the Paris Agreement, although important, may not be enough on its own to limit warming.",
   opts:["It legally forces every country to meet strict, enforceable targets","It bans all use of fossil fuels worldwide immediately","It applies only to a handful of small nations","Its targets are voluntary with no enforcement, and current pledges fall short, so national policy and individual action are also needed"], c:3,
   e:"The Paris Agreement is important for global coordination, but its Nationally Determined Contributions are voluntary with no enforcement mechanism, and current pledges are insufficient to keep warming to 1.5 °C. Real progress also needs strong national policy, business action and individual behaviour change. It does not impose enforceable targets or an immediate global fossil-fuel ban, and it covers 196 countries, not just a few."}
]);

QUESTIONS["g10i-01-4"] = (QUESTIONS["g10i-01-4"] || []).concat([
  {q:"A rotating tropical storm that forms in the north-west Pacific, affecting Japan and the Philippines, is called what?",
   opts:["A hurricane","A typhoon","A cyclone","A tornado"], c:1,
   e:"In the north-west Pacific these storms are called typhoons. The same phenomenon is called a hurricane in the North Atlantic and north-east Pacific, and a cyclone in the Indian Ocean and around Australia. A tornado is a different, much smaller and shorter-lived rotating storm formed over land, not a tropical storm formed over warm ocean water."},
  {q:"In which broad latitude band do most tropical storms form?",
   opts:["Directly on the Equator (0°)","Between roughly 5° and 30° north and south of the Equator","Between 60° and 90° (near the poles)","Only in the Southern Hemisphere"], c:1,
   e:"Most tropical storms form between about 5° and 30° north and south of the Equator, where the ocean is warm enough and the Coriolis effect is strong enough to create spin. They do not form on the Equator itself because there the Coriolis effect is too weak, and the polar latitudes are far too cold. They form in both hemispheres, not only the south."},
  {q:"What causes a storm surge during a tropical storm?",
   opts:["Low central pressure letting the sea rise, combined with strong winds piling water against the coast","Heavy rainfall filling rivers inland","An undersea earthquake beneath the storm","Cold water rising from the deep ocean"], c:0,
   e:"A storm surge is caused by the storm's very low central pressure allowing the sea surface to bulge upwards, while powerful onshore winds drive water against the coast. This raises sea levels and floods low-lying land, often causing the most deaths. River flooding from rainfall is a separate effect, and a surge is a weather process, not the result of an earthquake, which would cause a tsunami instead."},
  {q:"Why is a storm surge often deadlier than the high winds of a tropical storm?",
   opts:["Winds never cause any damage","It rapidly floods low-lying coastal areas, drowning people and contaminating land and water","It only occurs far out at sea","It cools the storm and makes it stronger"], c:1,
   e:"A storm surge can flood large areas of low-lying coast within minutes, drowning people and livestock, destroying buildings and contaminating farmland and fresh water with salt. This is why surges, such as the 5 m surge in Tacloban during Typhoon Haiyan, often cause a high proportion of deaths. High winds are destructive too, but the surge frequently causes the greatest loss of life; it strikes the coast, not just the open sea."},
  {q:"Which sequence correctly describes the formation of a tropical storm?",
   opts:["Air sinks and cools, then the ocean freezes, then winds calm","Warm air rises creating low pressure, water vapour condenses releasing latent heat, the Coriolis effect makes the system spin","Cold polar air sinks, spreads out and warms the sea","Rainfall on land evaporates and forms a storm out at sea"], c:1,
   e:"A tropical storm forms when warm, moist air over a warm ocean rises rapidly, creating intense low pressure. As the air cools, water vapour condenses, releasing latent heat that fuels further uplift, and the Coriolis effect makes the system spin. The other options reverse or muddle the process; sinking, cooling or freezing air would suppress a storm rather than create one."},
  {q:"In the eye of a tropical storm, conditions are best described as which of the following?",
   opts:["The most violent winds and heaviest rain","Permanent darkness and freezing temperatures","Calm, with light winds, clear skies and the lowest pressure","Identical to the spiralling rain bands"], c:2,
   e:"The eye is a central column of calm, sinking air, typically 30–50 km across, with light winds, clear skies and the lowest pressure in the storm. The most violent winds and heaviest rain are found in the eyewall surrounding it, not in the eye. This is why people experience a brief lull as the eye passes overhead before the eyewall returns from the opposite direction."},
  {q:"Why is it misleading to judge a tropical storm's danger by its wind-speed category alone?",
   opts:["Wind speed is the only thing that ever causes deaths","The scale ignores rainfall and storm surge, which often cause the most deaths and flooding","Higher categories are always less dangerous","Wind speed cannot be measured"], c:1,
   e:"A wind-speed scale such as the Saffir-Simpson scale only measures sustained wind speed. It does not capture rainfall totals or storm-surge height, which frequently cause the greatest flooding and loss of life. A 'lower category' storm that stalls and dumps huge rainfall can be deadlier than a brief high-category one, so category alone gives an incomplete picture of the hazard."},
  {q:"Which of these is the clearest example of a long-term response to a tropical storm?",
   opts:["Rescuing people trapped by floodwater on the first day","Rebuilding homes to be storm-resistant and improving early warning systems over the following years","Distributing emergency food and water immediately after landfall","Setting up temporary shelters in the first week"], c:1,
   e:"Long-term responses take place over weeks, months or years and aim to rebuild and reduce future risk. Rebuilding storm-resistant homes and improving warning systems are clear examples. Rescuing trapped people, handing out emergency supplies and erecting temporary shelters all happen in the immediate aftermath, so they are immediate responses rather than long-term ones."},
  {q:"Replanting mangroves along a coast is recommended after some tropical storms. Why does this help?",
   opts:["Mangroves stop storms from forming over the ocean","Mangroves raise the sea temperature","Mangroves block all rainfall from reaching land","Mangroves absorb wave and storm-surge energy and trap sediment, protecting the coast behind them"], c:3,
   e:"Mangrove forests act as a natural buffer: their dense roots and trunks absorb the energy of waves and storm surges and trap sediment, reducing flooding and erosion along the coast behind them. This is why mangrove replanting featured in the response to Typhoon Haiyan. They cannot stop storms forming far out at sea, change sea temperature or block rainfall; they reduce the surge reaching the shore."},
  {q:"Evaluate why evacuation before a tropical storm can be difficult, even when a warning is issued.",
   opts:["Warnings always guarantee everyone leaves safely","Uncertainty over the exact track, limited transport, cost, and people unwilling to leave homes and livestock can all reduce its success","Evacuation makes the storm stronger","Tropical storms give no warning at all"], c:1,
   e:"Even with several days' warning, forecasts cannot pinpoint the exact landfall, so authorities may evacuate the wrong area or hesitate. Limited transport, the cost of moving and sheltering people, and reluctance to abandon homes, livestock or property can all reduce how many leave. Effective evacuation therefore needs good planning and communication. Warnings do not strengthen storms, and modern storms are usually tracked for days."}
]);

QUESTIONS["g10i-01-5"] = (QUESTIONS["g10i-01-5"] || []).concat([
  {q:"In hazard terminology, when does a natural hazard become a 'disaster'?",
   opts:["As soon as any natural event occurs, even in an empty area","When a hazard seriously affects a vulnerable population, causing major loss or disruption they cannot cope with alone","Only when scientists predict it in advance","Only if it happens at a constructive plate boundary"], c:1,
   e:"A hazard is a natural event that threatens people, but it becomes a disaster only when it seriously affects a vulnerable population, causing major loss of life or damage they cannot cope with unaided. An identical event in an empty area is just a natural event, not a disaster. It is the combination of hazard and human vulnerability, not prediction or boundary type, that creates a disaster."},
  {q:"Which factor increases the risk that a hazard becomes a disaster?",
   opts:["A small, wealthy, well-prepared population living far from the hazard","A large, poor population living in exposed, poorly built housing close to the hazard","Strict building codes that are enforced","Regular emergency drills and education"], c:1,
   e:"Risk rises where many people are exposed and vulnerable. A large, poor population in exposed, poorly built housing close to the hazard is highly vulnerable, so a hazard there is far more likely to become a disaster. Wealth, distance from the hazard, enforced building codes and regular drills all reduce vulnerability and therefore lower the risk, rather than raising it."},
  {q:"On the Park model (hazard-response curve), which stage involves restoring temporary services such as shelter, water and power in the days and weeks after an event?",
   opts:["Pre-disaster","Relief","Rehabilitation","No stage involves restoring services"], c:2,
   e:"The Park model has four stages: pre-disaster (normal life), relief (the immediate emergency response of search and rescue), rehabilitation (restoring temporary services such as shelter, water and power over days to weeks) and reconstruction (long-term rebuilding). Restoring temporary services therefore belongs to the rehabilitation stage, which bridges the immediate relief effort and full reconstruction."},
  {q:"According to the Park model, how does good preparation before a hazard affect the response curve?",
   opts:["It has no effect on the curve","It makes the drop in quality of life shallower and recovery quicker","It makes the disaster last much longer","It removes the need for any reconstruction"], c:1,
   e:"The Park model shows that better preparation, such as drills, defences and emergency planning, makes the fall in quality of life shallower and the recovery faster, and a community may even end up better off if it 'builds back better'. Preparation clearly changes the shape of the curve; it does not lengthen the disaster, and reconstruction is still needed to rebuild what was damaged."},
  {q:"Why do many people choose to farm on the fertile slopes of volcanoes such as Mount Etna?",
   opts:["Weathered volcanic ash and lava break down into very fertile soils ideal for growing crops","Volcanic eruptions improve crop prices","Volcanoes guarantee there will be no earthquakes","The slopes are always completely safe from eruptions"], c:0,
   e:"Over time, weathered volcanic ash and lava break down into mineral-rich, fertile soils that are excellent for farming, which is why people cultivate the slopes of volcanoes like Etna. People weigh this benefit against the risk. The soil is the draw, not eruption effects on prices. Living there does not prevent earthquakes, and the slopes are certainly not free from eruption danger."},
  {q:"Why is reliable short-term prediction possible for many volcanoes but not for earthquakes?",
   opts:["Volcanoes are always larger than earthquakes","Rising magma gives measurable warning signs, but there is no consistent detectable signal for exactly when a fault will rupture","Earthquakes only happen in unpopulated areas","Scientists deliberately avoid monitoring earthquakes"], c:1,
   e:"Before an eruption, rising magma produces measurable warning signs: small tremors, ground swelling, raised temperatures and changing gas emissions, which can be monitored to forecast eruptions and evacuate. Earthquakes give no consistent, detectable signal for exactly when a locked fault will slip, so reliable short-term prediction is not yet possible. This is why protection and planning matter most for earthquakes."},
  {q:"Which of these is an example of preparation (planning) rather than protection?",
   opts:["Fitting a building with rubber base isolators","Building a sea wall against tsunami","Holding regular evacuation drills and teaching 'drop, cover and hold on'","Strengthening a bridge with steel bracing"], c:2,
   e:"Planning prepares people and institutions before a hazard strikes. Regular evacuation drills and teaching protective actions such as 'drop, cover and hold on' are planning measures that reduce panic and casualties. Base isolators, sea walls and steel bracing are all forms of protection, which modify the built environment so it can physically withstand a hazard. The distinction is preparing people versus strengthening structures."},
  {q:"Why is education and drilling considered a cost-effective way to reduce earthquake deaths?",
   opts:["It is extremely expensive but only works in HICs","It is relatively low cost yet teaches large numbers of people protective actions that reduce casualties","It physically stops buildings from collapsing","It can accurately predict the next earthquake"], c:1,
   e:"Education and drills are inexpensive compared with rebuilding or constructing earthquake-resistant structures, yet they teach large numbers of people how to react, where to shelter and how to avoid fires, which significantly reduces casualties. Japan's annual drills are a good example. They do not strengthen buildings (that is protection) or predict earthquakes; their value lies in cheaply preparing the population to respond."},
  {q:"A high-income country and a low-income country face the same volcanic threat. Why might their ability to manage the risk differ?",
   opts:["The hazard is always weaker in low-income countries","Low-income countries can always predict eruptions more accurately","The high-income country can afford monitoring equipment, evacuation transport and enforcement of building rules, while the low-income country may not","Wealth makes no difference to hazard management"], c:2,
   e:"Wealth strongly affects the capacity to manage hazards. A high-income country can fund seismometers and gas sensors, organise and transport evacuees, enforce building regulations and run education programmes. A low-income country may lack the money and infrastructure for these, leaving people more exposed. The hazard itself is not weaker in poorer countries, and prediction depends on equipment that wealth helps provide."},
  {q:"Evaluate why a combination of prediction, protection and planning is usually recommended for tectonic hazards.",
   opts:["One strategy alone is always sufficient","Each strategy has weaknesses, so combining them covers different hazards and stages — for example planning and protection compensate where earthquake prediction fails","Using several strategies is always the cheapest option","Prediction alone can prevent earthquakes occurring"], c:1,
   e:"No single approach is enough: prediction works for volcanoes but not earthquakes, protection is effective but costly, and planning is cheap but needs public cooperation. Combining them means the weakness of one is covered by another, so where earthquakes cannot be predicted, earthquake-resistant building and well-rehearsed drills still save lives. Combining strategies is not necessarily cheapest, and nothing can prevent the earthquake itself."}
]);

QUESTIONS["g10i-01-6"] = (QUESTIONS["g10i-01-6"] || []).concat([
  {q:"Why does the UK experience such varied and changeable weather?",
   opts:["It lies where several different air masses meet, in the path of mid-latitude depressions","It lies on a major plate boundary","It is located within the tropics","It has no surrounding ocean to influence it"], c:0,
   e:"The UK sits where several contrasting air masses meet — tropical maritime, polar maritime, polar continental and others — and in the path of mid-latitude depressions carried on the prevailing south-westerly winds. This mix gives it frequent, changeable weather. The UK is not on a plate boundary, is well outside the tropics, and is strongly influenced by the surrounding Atlantic Ocean."},
  {q:"The cold, dry 'Beast from the East' that brought heavy snow to the UK in 2018 came from which air mass?",
   opts:["Tropical maritime from the south-west","Polar continental from the cold east","Tropical continental from the south","Tropical maritime from the warm Atlantic"], c:1,
   e:"The 'Beast from the East' was polar continental air drawn from the cold European and Russian landmass to the east, bringing freezing temperatures and heavy snow. Tropical maritime air from the south-west brings mild, wet weather, and tropical continental air from the south brings summer heatwaves. The key clue is that the air was cold and dry and came from the east."},
  {q:"As a warm front passes over the UK in a depression, what weather is typically experienced?",
   opts:["Sudden heavy showers and a sharp drop in temperature","Clear skies and rising pressure","Thickening cloud followed by steady, prolonged rain as warm air rises gently over cold air","Freezing fog and frost"], c:2,
   e:"At a warm front, warm air rises gently over cold air ahead of it, producing thickening cloud and steady, prolonged rain. The sharp showers and sudden temperature drop come later, at the cold front, where cold air undercuts the warm air more steeply. Clear skies and rising pressure follow once the depression has passed, not as the warm front arrives."},
  {q:"Why does a cold front in a depression usually bring heavier, more sudden rainfall than a warm front?",
   opts:["The cold air is much wetter than the warm air","Cold air undercuts the warm air and forces it to rise steeply, causing rapid uplift and intense rain","The cold front brings no cloud at all","Warm fronts never produce any rain"], c:1,
   e:"At a cold front, dense cold air pushes under the warm air and forces it to rise steeply and quickly. This rapid uplift cools the air fast, condensing moisture into towering clouds and producing short, intense bursts of rain and gusty winds. A warm front rises more gently, giving lighter but more prolonged rain. It is the steepness of the uplift, not the wetness of the cold air, that matters."},
  {q:"Which evidence best supports the claim that UK weather is becoming more extreme?",
   opts:["The UK has never recorded a temperature above 35 °C","The UK exceeded 40 °C for the first time on record in July 2022","Named winter storms have become rarer","UK winters are becoming drier and colder"], c:1,
   e:"In July 2022 the UK exceeded 40 °C for the first time on record (40.3 °C at Coningsby), which, alongside record rainfall and more frequent named storms, supports the idea of increasingly extreme weather consistent with a warming climate. The other options are false: the UK has exceeded 35 °C, named storms have become more frequent, and winters are trending wetter, not drier and colder."},
  {q:"What was a key human factor that worsened the Somerset Levels floods of 2013–2014?",
   opts:["A volcanic eruption upstream","Excessive groundwater pumping for a city","Construction of a large dam that later burst","The rivers Tone and Parrett had not been dredged for over 20 years, reducing their capacity"], c:3,
   e:"A key human factor was that the rivers Tone and Parrett had not been dredged for more than 20 years, reducing their capacity to carry water away. Combined with record winter rainfall, flat low-lying land and high tides blocking drainage, this kept large areas under water for weeks. There was no volcano, the area is rural rather than supplied by city groundwater pumping, and no dam burst was involved."},
  {q:"Which of these was an economic (rather than social or environmental) effect of the Somerset Levels floods?",
   opts:["Villages such as Moorland being evacuated","Over 14,000 hectares of farmland flooded for weeks, with losses costing over £10 million","Floodwater contaminated with sewage and oil","Habitats damaged by prolonged inundation"], c:1,
   e:"Economic effects involve money, jobs and businesses. Over 14,000 hectares of farmland being flooded for weeks, with damage costing over £10 million, is an economic effect. Evacuating villages is a social effect (it affects people and communities), while contaminated water and damaged habitats are environmental effects. Sorting impacts into social, economic and environmental is a common exam requirement."},
  {q:"Why is dredging a river an example of hard engineering for flood management?",
   opts:["It works only with natural processes and adds no structures","It physically alters the river channel using machinery to increase its capacity to carry water","It involves planting trees across the floodplain","It relies entirely on letting the floodplain flood naturally"], c:1,
   e:"Dredging uses machinery to deepen and widen the river channel, physically altering it to increase how much water it can carry, which makes it a form of hard engineering. Soft engineering works with natural processes, such as tree planting, floodplain restoration and allowing land to flood naturally to store water. The defining feature of hard engineering is the deliberate, built modification of the channel."},
  {q:"Why might soft engineering, such as tree planting upstream, be preferred over hard defences in some catchments?",
   opts:["It is usually cheaper, benefits wildlife and water quality, and slows run-off across the whole catchment","It gives instant, complete protection against any flood","It removes the need to protect towns at all","It always works better than hard engineering in every situation"], c:1,
   e:"Soft engineering, such as upstream tree planting and floodplain restoration, is generally cheaper, slows run-off across the catchment and brings benefits for wildlife and water quality. However, it acts slowly, needs large areas of land and may not cope with extreme events alone, so it does not give instant or complete protection. A combined approach often protects high-value towns with hard defences while using soft measures to reduce overall run-off."},
  {q:"Evaluate the most effective approach to managing flooding in a UK river catchment that includes a major town.",
   opts:["Use only soft engineering everywhere and abandon all hard defences","Combine soft engineering across the catchment to slow run-off with hard defences to protect the high-value urban area","Rely solely on dredging the river once","Do nothing and allow all areas to flood"], c:1,
   e:"A catchment-wide strategy that combines soft engineering, slowing and storing run-off upstream through tree planting and floodplain restoration, with hard defences such as flood walls protecting the densely built town is usually most effective. Soft measures alone may not protect a major town in an extreme event, while hard defences alone can be costly and shift water downstream. Dredging once, or doing nothing, would leave the town exposed."}
]);
